            <ce:date-received day="13" month="9" year="2024"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="29" month="11" year="2024"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="2" month="12" year="2024"/>
            <ce:abstract id="ab0010" class="author" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="abs0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">Fire is a major driver of forest degradation and biodiversity loss in the Amazon. Although some studies have evaluated the impacts of fire on forest structure and diversity, uncertainties remain, particularly regarding how increased fire frequency affects species composition and carbon dynamics in seasonal forests of the southern Amazon. Here, we tested two hypotheses: (1) increased fire frequency alters floristic composition and reduces alpha diversity, number of tree species, stem density, and carbon stocks; and (2) after fire, tree species that prefer forest habitats decline, while cerrado and generalist species increase. We surveyed all trees with a diameter greater than 15 cm across 14 plots (10 ×100 m) in single-burned, multiple-burned and unburned primary forests. Our results showed significant shifts in species composition, as well as reductions in aboveground carbon stocks and stem density following fires, which demonstrates the sensitivity of these forests to fire events. In contrast, the lack of variation in the number of tree species and alpha diversity among forest classes suggests that these parameters are not reliable predictors of the effects of fire. Increased fire frequency led to a decline in forest-preferring species, while the numbers of cerrado and generalist species remained stable. Our findings indicate that frequent fires are reshaping forest structure and homogenizing species composition, reducing typical forest species while favoring open-area and generalist species in burned forests. This provides evidence of a potential adaptation in species composition, indicating a process of biotic homogenization driven by forest degradation following single or multiple burns.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            
            <ce:keywords id="keys0005" class="keyword" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="key0005">
                  <ce:text>Biotic homogenization</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0010">
                  <ce:text>Diversity</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0015">
                  <ce:text>Carbon stocks</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0020">
                  <ce:text>Degradation</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0025">
                  <ce:text>Tipping point</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0030">
                  <ce:text>Wildfires</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0020">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Data will be made available on request.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec0005" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">The conversion of native vegetation through deforestation and degradation are the main factors responsible for biodiversity loss and climate change in tropical forests (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0005" refid="bib5 bib29 bib52">Barlow et al., 2016; Marengo et al., 2022; Silva et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Currently, the area of forest degraded exceeds that deforested in Amazonia, with fire, fragmentation, and logging as the main factors transforming the landscape (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0050" refid="bib32">Matricardi et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Degradation has increased over the last decade in the region, especially from fire, with the states of Mato Grosso and Pará showing the largest burned areas (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0010" refid="bib14 bib52">Da Ponte et al., 2023; Silva et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">There are three primary types of fires in the Amazon: (i) fires associated with deforestation; (ii) fires related to pasture management; and (iii) forest fires that occur when managed burns escape control and spread into forested areas (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0055" refid="bib4">Barlow et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). These fires events cause major losses in biodiversity and significant changes in forest structure (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0015" refid="bib7 bib54 bib41">Berenguer et al., 2018; Silvério et al., 2019; Rangel Pinagé et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>), alpha diversity and species composition (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0020" refid="bib24 bib13">França et al., 2020; Costa et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Additionally, fires increase Brazil's annual atmospheric carbon emissions by up to 50 %, with a significant portion originating from deforestation and degradation activities in the Amazon (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0025" refid="bib3 bib51">Aragão et al., 2018; Silva et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Several natural and anthropogenic factors can act as positive feedback for forest fires. Fragmentation and proximity to agricultural areas (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0060" refid="bib56">Tavares et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), increased precipitation seasonality (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0030" refid="bib8 bib57">Brando et al., 2014; Valente and Laurini, 2023</ce:cross-refs>), and extreme drought conditions driven by El Niño events (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0065" refid="bib59">Withey et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) are factors that exacerbate the spread and intensity of forest fires. In fragmented forests, the increase in light, temperature and wind speed causes greater tree mortality in forest edges and favors the colonization of exotic grasses (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0070" refid="bib54">Silvério et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). These changes increase combustible material in the litter and, consequently, forest flammability, contributing to increased fire severity and fire recurrence (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0035" refid="bib8 bib54">Brando et al., 2014; Silvério et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). Fire scars on trees surviving fires make them more susceptible to breakage due to strong winds, leading to increased mortality (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0040" refid="bib54 bib44">Silvério et al., 2019; Reis et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). These changes in the structure and composition of species in burned forests have caused a cycle of erosion of biodiversity and ecosystem services (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0045" refid="bib5 bib53">Barlow et al., 2016; Silva et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>). A phenomenon known as late dieback can result in long-term effects following fire, with the effects of a single fire event being observed in the tree community for up to 30 years (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0075" refid="bib51">Silva et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">The Transition Zone (ZOT) between Amazon and Cerrado biomes is approximately 4500 km long and is characterized by a mosaic of vegetation, with savannas and forests coexisting side by side (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0050" refid="bib30 bib17">Marimon et al., 2006; Elias et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). This region exhibits higher deforestation rates and extreme weather conditions (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0055" refid="bib31 bib32 bib29">Marques et al., 2020; Matricardi et al., 2020; Marengo et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). These extreme environmental conditions lead to increased vulnerability of vegetation to fire, underscoring the need for further research into the causes and consequences of repeated fires in the ZOT.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Contemporary forests in Amazonia are also experiencing sub-decadal fire return intervals compared to historical return intervals spanning centuries (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0080" refid="bib21">Feldpausch et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). While some studies provide valuable insights into the impacts of up to two fire events on the tree dynamics and productivity (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0060" refid="bib28 bib53 bib6">Maracahipes et al., 2014; Silva et al., 2018; Berenguer et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>), others, such as the Tanguro Project, have examined consequences of more frequent burns. The Tanguro Project tested the effects of prescribed fires occurring annually and every three years on biodiversity across a total area of 100 ha. The results showed that fires every three years were more harmful to specific biodiversity groups than annual fires (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0085" refid="bib8">Brando et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Furthermore, the fires significantly reduced the aboveground carbon stocks and accumulation (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0065" refid="bib49 bib10 bib54">Rocha et al., 2014; Brando et al., 2019; Silvério et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>) and caused profound changes in species composition (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0070" refid="bib10 bib54 bib40">Brando et al., 2019; Silvaério et al., 2019; Prestes et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>). However, with these results being spatially limited with no replicates, new assessments are needed in other regions of ZOT.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">Estimates suggest that profound changes are occurring or have already take place in the ZOT. For instance, forests in this region have lost their natural ability to mitigate atmospheric carbon in some locations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0090" refid="bib25">Gatti et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) and exhibit the highest tree mortality rates within the Biome (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0095" refid="bib19">Esquivel-Muelbert et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). The loss of tree species killed by fire and/or those sensitive to post-fire conditions may be driving significant floristic shifts, pushing these forests toward an alternative stable state that is less diverse and functionally redundant (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0075" refid="bib22 bib23 bib53 bib55">Filgueiras et al., 2021; Flores et al., 2024; Silva et al., 2018; Tabarelli et al., 2012</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">In this study, we evaluated the impact of increased fire frequency on number of tree species, alpha diversity, species composition, stem density, and aboveground carbon stocks of trees in seasonal forest in southern Amazonia. We compared these parameters among forests with single burns, multiple burns, and adjacent unburned forests. We identified indicator species for each forest class, evaluated their responses to fire, and compared their physiognomic preferences (cerrado, forest, or generalist). We tested two hypotheses: (1) increased fire frequency alters floristic composition and reduces alpha diversity, number of tree species, stem density, and carbon stocks in seasonal forests by increasing tree mortality, which raises forest flammability through more combustible material and higher ground temperatures (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0080" refid="bib49 bib10 bib54">Rocha et al., 2014; Brando et al., 2019; Silvério et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>); (2) after fire, tree species that prefer forest environment decline while cerrado and generalist species increase. Fires exclude sensitive species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0085" refid="bib55 bib53 bib22">Tabarelli et al., 2012; Silva et al., 2018; Filgueiras et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>), making forest species more vulnerable due to their lack of fire adaptations, such as thick bark that can withstand high temperatures (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0090" refid="bib54 bib46">Silvério et al., 2019; Reis et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Finally, we discuss the main challenges and implications associated with fires in seasonal forests at the southern edge of the Amazon.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0010" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0030">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0035">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">The study was carried out in 14 plots located in seasonal forests in the municipality of Confresa, in the northeast region of the state of Mato Grosso, within Transition Zone (ZOT) between the Amazon and Cerrado biomes (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0100" refid="sec0070">Figure SI 1</ce:cross-ref>). This region is characterized by a mosaic composed of forest and savanna typical of both biomes (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0095" refid="bib42 bib30 bib26">Ratter et al., 1973; Marimon et al., 2006; Ivanauskas et al., 2008</ce:cross-refs>). The predominant land use around the studied forest fragments is mechanized agriculture, pastures, and selectively logged forests (Figure SI 1).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">The climate is characterized as Köppen's Aw, with two distinct climatic periods (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0105" refid="bib2">Alvares et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>), a dry period from May to September, and a rainy period from October to April. The annual precipitation variation over the last decade (2012–2022) ranged from 1672 mm in 2022–2235 mm in 2018, with an average of 2020 mm (Figure SI 2). The predominant soil in the region is sandy-textured, dystrophic, alic Red-Yellow Oxisols (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0110" refid="bib26">Ivanauskas et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0040">Experimental design</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">For data collection, we installed 14 plots (10 ×100 m each) in primary forests areas in 2023: five plots in single-burned, four in multiple-burned, and five in unburned forests (baseline). All plots were installed in forest fragments greater than 200 ha. We delimited these forest classes based on the analysis of high-resolution fire frequency images (30 m) from the MapBiomas Fogo 2.0 database (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0115" refid="bib1">Alencar et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) and performed in the QGis 3.32.1 Program (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0120" refid="bib16">QGIS Development Team, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). The burning events in the single-burn plots occurred in 1998 (two areas), 2005, 2007 and 2010. In the multiple-burn plots, there were three to four burning events, with the last ones occurring in 1994, 2007 (see <ce:cross-ref id="cr0125" refid="sec0070">Table SI 1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">In each plot, we measured the total height (m) and stem diameter at 1.3 m above the ground of all tree individuals and palms larger than 15 cm diameter. We identified individuals in the field, and when necessary, we collected samples for comparison with vouchers from the Herbário TRAN at IFMT-Campus Confresa. We classified each species based on their environmental preferences as typical of the cerrado (Brazilian savanna), forest (occurring only in forest physiognomies), or generalist (occurring in both cerrado and forest), from our extensive knowledge and field experience regarding the autecology of the evaluated species.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0045">Description of the evaluated parameters</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">For each plot, we determined: the number of tree species (number of tree species/area);stem density (stems/ha); alpha diversity, using the Shannon Index (H’) calculated by the ‘vegan’ package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0130" refid="bib37">Oksanen et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>); and aboveground carbon stocks estimated from aboveground biomass (AGB) values calculated for each individual in the plots using the equation by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0135" refid="bib11">Chave et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref> performed in the ‘BIOMASS’ package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0140" refid="bib47">Réjou-Méchain et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). To calculate AGB, we used diameter and height values collected in the field, while wood density was extracted from the Global Wood Density Database (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0145" refid="bib60">Zanne et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0050">Data analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">To test our first hypothesis that increased fire frequency alters floristic composition and reduces alpha diversity, number of tree species, stem density, and carbon stocks, we used the following analyses. For floristic composition, we applied the Multiple Response Permutation Procedure based on the Bray-Curtis distance index available in the ‘vegan’ package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0150" refid="bib37">Oksanen et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). The visualization of floristic distances among the evaluated forest classes (single-burned, multiple-burned, and unburned forests) was represented by a dendrogram. We also used an ordination graph to display the species replacement between forest classes. Additionally, we evaluated the indicator value of species across forest classes using the IND VAL analysis, implemented in the ‘labdsv’ package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0155" refid="bib48">Roberts and Roberts, 2016</ce:cross-ref>). For the remaining parameters, we compared the means between forest classes using ANOVA with Tukey’s multiple comparisons test (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0160" refid="bib61">Zar, 2010</ce:cross-ref>), performed via the 'stats' package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0165" refid="bib50">R Core Team, 2024</ce:cross-ref>). ANOVA assumptions were checked through graphical analysis of residuals.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">To test our second hypothesis, that tree species preferring forest environments decline after fire while cerrado and generalist species increase, we compared the proportions of species’ physiognomic preferences (cerrado, forest, and generalists) using the Z-test from the ‘stats’ package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0170" refid="bib12">R Core Team, 2024</ce:cross-ref>). All analyses and graphs were performed in R version 4.4.1 (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0175" refid="bib50">R Core Team, 2024</ce:cross-ref>) at alpha level of 5 %.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0035" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0055">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0060">Floristic description</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">We recorded a total of 70 species, including 54 in unburned, 38 in single-burned, and 35 in multiple-burned forests (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0180" refid="sec0070">Table SI 1</ce:cross-ref>). Among these, 16 species occurred exclusively in unburned, five in single-burned, and seven in multiple-burned forests. Some of the species exclusive to unburned forests included <ce:italic>Andira vermifuga</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Couepia grandiflora</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Pseudolmedia laevigata</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Xylopia amazonica</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Ficus paraensis</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Inga capitata</ce:italic>. Species exclusive in the single-burn plots included <ce:italic>Cecropia palmata</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Chaetocarpus echinocarpus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Euplassa inaequalis</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Schoepfia lucida</ce:italic>, while those exclusive to multiple-burn plots included <ce:italic>Byrsonima cydoniifolia</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Roupala montana</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Maprounea guianensis</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Cheiloclinium cognatum</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Hymenaea courbaril</ce:italic> (Table SI 2). Furthermore, 16 species occurred in all three forest classes (e.g., <ce:italic>Byrsonima crispa</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Connarus perrotteti</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Himatanthus articulatus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Ocotea longifolia</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Tachigali vulgaris</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Vismia guianensis</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Tapirira guianensis</ce:italic>), while four species occurred only in the burned forests (i.e., <ce:italic>Apeiba tibourbou</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Ilex</ce:italic> sp., <ce:italic>Jacaranda copaia</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Oenocarpus distichus</ce:italic>). The predominant family among all plots was Fabaceae (with 10 species), followed by Burseraceae (5), Chrysobalanaceae (5), Annonaceae (5), Melastomataceae (3) and Moraceae (3).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0045" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0065">Comparison of evaluated parameters</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">The species composition of multiple-burned forests had significant variability compared to unburned and single-burned forests (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0005"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0185" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>), with distinct replacement of species along the fire frequency gradient (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0010"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0190" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). This finding supports our first hypothesis, indicating that increased burn frequency influences floristic composition. According to the INDVAL analysis, <ce:italic>Sacoglottis guianensis</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Tachigali vulgaris</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Byrsonima cydoniifolia</ce:italic> were identified as indicator species of the unburned, single-burned and multiple-burned floristic groups, respectively (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0195" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0200" refid="sec0070">Table SI 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">Comparing the physiognomic preference of species across forest classes showed a significant reduction of typical-forest species in burned areas, regardless of fire frequency, while there was no significant difference in typical-cerrado or generalist species among burn frequency classes (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0015"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0205" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>), suggesting that while fire frequency impacts forest-specific species, it may not affect generalist species as anticipated in our second hypothesis.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">The average alpha diversity (H’) was 2.4, 2.2, and 2.0 nats.ind<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>; stem density was 298, 206, and 155 ind.ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>; and carbon stocks were 25.5, 14.1 and 8 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in unburned, single-burned and multiple-burned forests, respectively (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0020"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0210" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0005"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0215" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). There was a trend of lower stem density and carbon stocks with increasing burn frequency; however, only multiple-burned forests had significantly lower values. Carbon stocks were (17.5 Mg C ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) lower in multiple burned forests compared to unburned forests (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0220" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>c-d). In contrast, the number of tree species and alpha diversity did not vary among the forest classes (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0225" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a-b), which may indicate that while fire affects species composition, it does not necessarily impact overall diversity metrics as hypothesized.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0050" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0070">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Our findings support our hypotheses that increased fire frequency significantly alters the structure and species composition of seasonal forests in the Amazon-Cerrado transition. We observed significant changes in species composition and reductions in carbon stocks and stem density. Specifically, increased fire frequency tends to homogenize species composition, reducing the presence of typical forest species and maintaining open area or generalist species along the fire gradient. These findings not only highlight the immediate impacts of fire events but also enhance our understanding of their effects on increasingly fragmented forests subjected to repeated fires, underscoring the potential long-term ecological consequences.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">The varying species composition between unburned and multiple-burned forests highlights the sensitivity of seasonal forests to fire events and confirms our first hypothesis. While the differences in the effects of single and multiple burns on the species composition suggest some degree of resilience, the altered species composition after multiples burns indicates biotic homogenization of floristic groups. This occurs when there is a reduction of sensitive species after multiple disturbances, like observed in seasonally flooded forests in the Amazonia (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0230" refid="bib53">Silva et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). The loss of typical forest species with increasing fire frequency in our forests reinforces this argument and demonstrates where floristic changes are occurring. In this case, forest species can be characterized as losers, with a significant reduction in population density or even local extinction (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0100" refid="bib55 bib22">Tabarelli et al., 2012; Filgueiras et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>). These modifications lead to profound changes in the structure, alpha diversity and natural dynamics of these communities in the post-fire period (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0105" refid="bib6 bib9 bib28">Berenguer et al., 2021; Brando et al., 2019; Maracahipes et al., 2014</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">In contrast, the lack of changes in the proportion of cerrado and generalist species with increasing fire frequency offers important insights into the future of these forests. Some studies in the Amazon suggested that forest degradation could lead to a process of savannization, where forests become ‘savannas’, resulting in significant impacts in the ecosystem services (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0235" refid="bib35">Nobre et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). However, our results do not support this hypothesis for tree flora. Despite the reduction in forest species, the numbers of cerrado (or savanna) and generalist species remained the same along the evaluated fire frequency gradient. Our findings indicate that floristic and structural change is driving these burned forests to an alternative stable state dissimilar to both unburned forest and cerrado, characterized by lower tree density, reduced carbon stocks and impoverished floristic composition. Instead of undergoing savannization, the tree flora of these forests appears to be experiencing biotic homogenization and degradation.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">The varying classification of indicator species among the forest classes shows that the floristic groups established in our plots are distinct. Although we did not observe a significant increase in cerrado and generalist species along the fire frequency gradient, the indication of the generalist species <ce:italic>T. vulgaris</ce:italic> and the cerrado species <ce:italic>B. cydoniifolia</ce:italic> in burned forests can be explained in two ways. First, these species may be opportunistic, with a high capacity for dispersal and colonization in open areas or clearings (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0240" refid="bib34">Morais et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; De <ce:cross-ref id="cr0245" refid="bib20">Farias et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>), which may explain their presence in burned areas where individuals of the canopy were killed (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0110" refid="bib18 bib43">Elias et al., 2013; Reis et al., 2015</ce:cross-refs>). Second, <ce:italic>B. cydoniifolia</ce:italic> may have a resistance to fire (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0250" refid="bib39">Pott and Pott, 1994</ce:cross-ref>), likely due to adaptive characteristics to xeric environments, such as thick bark providing thermal protection during fires (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0255" refid="bib46">Reis et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>) and preventing immediate or late mortality (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0260" refid="bib54">Silvério et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">In addition to changes in species composition, the observed loss of stem density and carbon stocks after burning also corroborates our first hypothesis and demonstrates the negative impacts of these events on forest dynamics and atmospheric carbon emissions. In regional terms, this result directly highlights how fires can negatively affect the ecosystem service for climate change mitigation by reducing the carbon stocks of seasonal forests in the southern Amazon region. Estimates indicate that the forest carbon balance is already compromised in this region, with these forests shifting from a carbon sink to a carbon source (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0265" refid="bib25">Gatti et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). These changes may be associated with high tree mortality in this region (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0270" refid="bib19">Esquivel-Muelbert et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>) due to fires (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0115" refid="bib28 bib53 bib36">Maracahipes et al., 2014; Silva et al., 2018; Nogueira et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>), especially during severe droughts (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0275" refid="bib59">Withey et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) and in areas near agricultural plantations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0280" refid="bib56">Tavares et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The region has a long history of indigenous land-use and occupation that may have affected ancient fire regimes (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0120" refid="bib38 bib58">Peripato et al., 2023; Watling et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Our analysis of burned forest is based on modern satellite imagery, so some forests classified as unburned forests may have burned in the decades before satellite data were available. The presence of pyrogenic carbon (macro and microscopic charcoal) in the soil in <ce:italic>terra firme</ce:italic> forests across the region indicates that all these forests likely burned over several centuries to millennia (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0125" refid="bib27 bib15">Koele et al., 2017; De Oliveira et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Forests that burned more recently in the pre-satellite period may still be recovering from fire or selected for fire-tolerant species. Although ancient fire histories could be reconstructed using charcoal radiocarbon dating (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0285" refid="bib21">Feldpausch et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), this approach is beyond the scope of our study.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Finally, the lack of variation in the number of tree species and alpha diversity among evaluated forest classes suggests that these parameters are not reliable predictors of the effects of fire on seasonal forests and do not support our initial hypothesis. This may be due to the ability of fire to both increase and decrease species diversity (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0290" refid="bib33">McLauchlan et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Furthermore, rapid colonization by light-dependent pioneer species after fire may ensure that numbers of tree species remain stable between burned and unburned forests, despite there being important floristic differences as observed in our plots. This occurs because fire eliminates sensitive floristic groups and induces the spontaneous colonization of functionally similar or closely related species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0130" refid="bib55 bib43 bib53">Tabarelli et al., 2012; Reis et al., 2015; Silva et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Our results provide evidence of fire-driven forest degradation in the southern Amazon. Considering the history and trends of increasing frequency of degradation and severe drought events across the Amazon biome (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0135" refid="bib32 bib29">Matricardi et al., 2020; Marengo et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>), it is likely that this process of biotic homogenization of species composition is occurring in other areas or may occur over the coming decades. These changes call for immediate actions to reduce wildfires and degradation to avoid a biome-wide shift to a new, stable, and impoverished forest state.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">It is important to acknowledge that our approach is limited to assessing the effects of fires and their frequencies. However, other degradation factors not analyzed in this study may also influence these parameters. For instance, forest fragmentation, selective logging, soil conditions and litter deposition are known to significantly affect forest structure and tree diversity under fire events (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0140" refid="bib45 bib36 bib54">Reis et al., 2018; Nogueira et al., 2019; Silvério et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0055" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0075">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Beatriz Schwantes Marimon:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing. <ce:bold>Ben Hur Marimon-Junior:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Supervision. <ce:bold>Fernando Elias:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Visualization, Validation, Supervision, Project administration, Methodology, Formal analysis, Conceptualization. <ce:bold>Maurivan Barros Pereira:</ce:bold> Writing – original draft, Methodology, Investigation, Funding acquisition, Formal analysis, Data curation, Conceptualization. <ce:bold>Ted R. Feldpausch:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Supervision. <ce:bold>Nayara Dias Alves Teixeira:</ce:bold> Writing – original draft, Supervision.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0080">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0085">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">The authors would like to thank the landowner partners for their support during sampling. To the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">SEDUC-MT</ce:grant-sponsor> and <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">SME-Confresa</ce:grant-sponsor> for financial support during the first author's doctoral studies. FE supported by the Serrapilheira Institute fellowship/<ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">FAPESPA</ce:grant-sponsor> (grant number – <ce:grant-number refid="spnsr3">R-2401–46863</ce:grant-number>). TRF was supported by a grant from the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">UK Natural Environment Research Council (NERC)</ce:grant-sponsor> and <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">São Paulo Research Foundation, Brazil (FAPESP)</ce:grant-sponsor> (<ce:grant-number refid="spnsr5">NE/N011570/1</ce:grant-number>, <ce:grant-number refid="spnsr5">NE/W001691/1</ce:grant-number>). BHMJR and BSM receive support from productivity fellowships PQ1 from the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Brazilian National Council for Scientific and Technological Development</ce:grant-sponsor> (<ce:grant-number refid="spnsr6">CNPq #311027/2019–9</ce:grant-number> and <ce:grant-number refid="spnsr6">#303492/2022–8</ce:grant-number>), as well as from the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr7" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">CNPq-PELD</ce:grant-sponsor> research project (<ce:grant-number refid="spnsr7">#441572/2020–0</ce:grant-number>) and the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr8" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Mato Grosso State Research Support Foundation</ce:grant-sponsor> (FAPEMAT - <ce:grant-number refid="spnsr8">#0346321/2020</ce:grant-number>). We also appreciate the valuable contributions of the two anonymous reviewers to the final manuscript.</ce:para>
               <ce:section id="sec0060" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0090">Declaration of Generative AI in Scientific Writing</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">During the preparation of this work, the authors used ChatGPT to check and improve the language of the manuscript. After using this tool, the authors reviewed and edited the content as needed and take full responsibility for the final content of the published article.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
